post_text:
Child Care

If your family is finding gaps in child care for the school year, the Olean
Family YMCA is available to support you.
In collaboration with the Olean School District, the Y will supplement
out-of-school time and offer child care, tutoring, and homework support.
Every student must be enrolled in one of the variety of plan options in
order to attend the program.
The Y is offering plan options to include:
● FULL-DAY CARE ON REMOTE LEARNING DAYS AT THE YMCA FOR
GRADES K-6
● AFTERSCHOOL ON IN-PERSON SCHOOL DAYS AT WASHINGTON WEST
AND EASTVIEW FOR GRADES K-3
● FOR THOSE ATTENDING OLEAN MIDDLE SCHOOL, GRADES 4-6, AFTER
SCHOOL CARE WILL AT THE YMCA. YMCA STAFF WILL WALK
STUDENTS FROM THE SCHOOL TO THE YMCA.
Registration is limited and the YMCA is accepting registrations now.
Parent packets are available at the Olean YMCA. We will be sending out
more information by the end of the week through our website, social
media, and email.
For more information on registration, contact the Olean YMCA at
716-373-2400

post_text: We are happy to confirm that our universal pre-kindergarten will be available for the upcoming school year in our district and Head Start classrooms. Students in our district universal pre-K classes at Eastview and Washington West may enroll in the red or gold hybrid model or in the 100% remote model. For students who have registered already, we will be contacting you to confirm your child’s class assignment and additional information. If you are interested in enrolling your child in pre-K at East View or Washington West please contact our central registrar, Mrs. Certo, at 716-375-8998. We’re excited to have our youngest huskies join the pack!

post_text:
WOW! Team Olean High School walked/ran/biked over 8,000 miles this school year, raising over $2,000 for charity!

Starting last fall, National Honor Society members, under the leadership of this year's President Mackenzie Windus, encouraged the students, faculty and staff at OHS to participate in a unique service project to raise money for charity. Charity Miles is an app that will donate $0.25/mile for each mile walked/biked/run to a national charity of the user's choice. Mackenzie quite literally ran with this idea and she and her mom raised over $600 for the Crohn's & Colitis Foundation of America. A huge thank you to our top 10 fundraisers as well. I think it is very impressive that both our Valedictorian (Maddie Hoffman) and our Salutatorian (Mackenzie Windus) are among the top 10 fundraisers. Simply incredible. Congrats to all!

Team Olean High School will remain open on the Charity Miles app for anyone who would like to join. It's available for free in the App Store.

GO HUSKIES!!!

post_text:
Good Morning Huskies and Husky Pups!
It is time to start production of the COVID 19 Circus of the Sun. This is a remote online circus which will be featured on our website. We are looking for talented Huskies and all Huskies have talent. We are looking for pictures of art work, poems, stories, dance routines, singing, playing your musical instrument, short movies or videos, slide shows, gymnastic routines, imitations of people, skits, lip synch, skateboard or bicycle tricks, magic acts, juggling, science projects, lego construction, new inventions, magic tricks, even stupid pet tricks. Just film them and store them on OneDrive and share them or e-mail them with your teacher, Principal and Mr. Lasky dlasky@oleanschools.org. We will review the submissions and then feature them on our website. Check the websites for information as they will start this week. Don’t be shy, it is about having fun.

post_text: The Olean Educational Support Personnel Association would like to recognize Julie Scull, who is celebrating 25 years in education. Julie began her career with the Olean City School district in January 1995 as a secretary in the special education/psychology department. In 2007 she transferred to the Middle School. In 2015 she began her current position as secretary to the athletic director. In addition to her secretarial duties, Julie is both past and current union president for the Olean Educational Support Staff Association. She enjoys interacting with the students and parents. She credits her longevity in the district with having a great staff, administration, and Board of Education to work with.

TONIGHT ONLY!
Screenagers: Growing Up in the Digital Age
“An award-winning film that probes into the vulnerable corners of family life and depicts messy struggles over social media, video games and academics. The film offers solutions on how we can help our kids navigate the digital world.”

OHS Auditorium
January 29th at 6:30 PM
Free and Open to the Public
For Info: Visit www.oleanschools.org or Call 375-8039

The Olean City School District will be hosting the presentation of Screenagers: Growing Up in the Digital Age on Wednesday, January 29th in the Olean High School auditorium at 6:30 PM. Screenagers is the first feature documentary to explore the impact of screen technology on kids and offer parents and families proven solutions that work. What started out as a personal story for one has grown into a national movement, helping millions of teens and their families navigate growing up in a world with instant access to screens.

https://www.screenagersmovie.com/press-release

post_text:
The Olean Teachers’ Association would like to recognize Olean Intermediate Middle School teacher Robin Charles, who is celebrating 30 years in education. Mrs. Charles started her teaching career in 1990 teaching grades 4 & 5 for ten years at Cattaraugus Elementary School. She was then hired by the Olean City School District in 2000 as a 4th grade teacher at Washington West elementary. In 2012 grades 4 & 5 moved to the Olean Intermediate Middle School where Mrs. Charles continues to teach 4th grade ELA, social studies, and science.
Mrs. Charles is a graduate of SUNY Fredonia where she earned both her Bachelor of Science and Master degrees in Education. During her time with Olean, Mrs. Charles has contributed outside of the classroom by serving on the ELA committee, the report card committee, the CIAC (Curriculum, Instruction, and Assessment Team) committee, and was a Technology Learning Team Leader. Congratulations to Mrs. Charles for her dedication and service to her students and the Olean City School District.

post_text: What an incredible day at finals today at the NYS swim tournament! Lex qualified for the 200 and the 100 finals yesterday at prelims. She was seeded 10th in her 200 and finished today with a time of 1:52.76, which was good enough for 8th in the public high school and 9th in the federation!! She was seeded 6th going into her 100 free today and finished today with a time of 51.44, which put her 3rd place in the public high schools and 5th in the federation!!! Thank you everyone who followed, supported and came out to show some support!! Her best finishes to date at the state tournament and looking forward to seeing what the near future holds for this young lady!!! Thanks for another great experience for all of us to be a part of and extending this outstanding fall season!!

Board of Education Vacancy

The Olean City School District is seeking potential candidates to fill a Board of Education seat that was vacated by Mr. Michael Martello on September 25, 2019.

For information regarding the vacancy, interested candidates can go to the Olean City School District website http://www.oleanschools.org. Posted on the website are the legal requirements to be eligible to serve on the BOE and a short questionnaire which must be submitted to the District Clerk no later than Wednesday, October 30, 2019.

ALL SPORTS MEETING FOR OHS STUDENT ATHLETES AND PARENTS/GUARDIANS

All Olean High School student-athletes planning to participate in Fall, Winter and Spring sports at the modified, JV, and varsity levels are welcome to attend this All-Sports informational meeting with a parent or guardian.

This important meeting, scheduled by the Athletic Department, will be held on Thursday, August 1, 2019 at 7:00 p.m. in the Olean High School auditorium.

The following topics will be discussed:
· Reviewing the Interscholastic Athletic Handbook for student-athletes and parents and guardians
· Information on how to register your student-athlete for a sports team (Family ID)
· Coaches contact information for all 3 seasons
· Break out sessions for all Fall teams only, by sport; coaches will review team rules, guidelines, and expectations

If you have any questions, please contact the Olean High School Athletic Office at 375-8042 or sanastasia@olean.wnyric.org.

post_text:
The Olean Educational Support Personnel Association would like to congratulate Noreen Cook on her retirement to be effective at the end of this school year. Noreen began her career as a Teacher's Aide at East View Elementary in September of 2000.

Noreen takes great pride in having been a positive influence in students' lives. One of her most memorable experiences was having a former student recognize her years later and give her a big hug and introduce her to his friends. She knew she had truly made an impression on him.

Noreen lives in Olean and has two sons. She also has four grandchildren who all attend East View Elementary.
The OESPA thanks you for your dedication to our students and wishes you much happiness in your retirement!

post_text:
The Olean Teachers’ Association would like to congratulate Joe Batesky on his retirement. Mr. Batesky began his career with the Olean City School District in September 1988, and has taught 7th grade social studies at Olean Middle School and Olean Intermediate Middle School for 30 years. He has enjoyed working with the students as an Olean Middle School basketball coach and an Olean JV football coach. Mr. Batesky has served as a Community Schools supervisor, and a teacher for the GED program and Homework Helpers.
Mr. Batesky is a graduate of Fairmont State College in West Virginia where he earned his Bachelor of Science Degree in Elementary Education, Health, Physical Education, and History. He then attended St. Bonaventure University where he received his Master of Science Degree in Reading. Congratulations to Mr. Batesky for his dedication and service to his students and the Olean City School District.

Way to go Mrs. Rhody and choir members!!

GO HUSKIES!!!

post_text: What a wonderful group of people! Olean City School District is proud to have them honored on the walls of Olean High School! Hope to see everyone at the induction ceremony on June 24th at 4:00 pm at OHS.
shared_text:
Olean Schools Foundation is with Pierre Eade and Jacquette M Timmons.
April 30, 2019 at 12:14 PM ·

Congratulations to the 2019 OCSD Wall of Honor Inductees: Fran Clawson, Pierre Eade, Casey Leigh and Jacquette Timmons! The Wall of Honor induction ceremony will be held on Friday June 14th at 4:00 PM at OHS. If you would like to attend, please email ocsdfoundation@gmail.com
